pshire, England":"英国史洛普爾","lifeSummary":"当Sir Richard de Puleston于1180年出生在英国史洛普爾时，他的父亲Roger de Pyvelesdon25岁，母亲Mrs Roger de Pyvelesdon21岁。他和Alice Lewis至少有1个儿子。他去世在英国。"},"hr":{"1180–":"1180.–preminuo","1180–Male":"1180.–preminuo","1184–Female":"1184–preminula","1198–1272":"1198.–1272","1155–Male":"1155–preminuo","1160–Female":"1160–preminula","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1155":"1155","1198":"1198.","1272":"1272","1184":"1184","1160":"1160","1180":"1180.","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","England":"England","Pyvelesdon, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England"},"cs":{"1180–":"1180–Zesnulý","1180–Male":"1180–Zesnulý","1184–Female":"1184–Zesnulá","1198–1272":"1198–1272","1155–Male":"1155–Zesnulý","1160–Female":"1160–Zesnulá","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1155":"1155","1198":"1198","1272":"1272","1184":"1184","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Anglie","England":"Anglie","Pyvelesdon, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Anglie"},"da":{"1180–":"1180–Afdød","1180–Male":"1180–Afdød","1184–Female":"1184–Afdød","1198–1272":"1198–1272","1155–Male":"1155–Afdød","1160–Female":"1160–Afdød","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1155":"1155","1198":"1198","1272":"1272","1184":"1184","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","England":"England","Pyvelesdon, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England"},"nl":{"1180–":"1180–Overleden","1180–Male":"1180–Overleden","1184–Female":"1184–Overleden","1198–1272":"1198–1272","1155–Male":"1155–Overleden","1160–Female":"1160–Overleden","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1155":"1155","1198":"1198","1272":"1272","1184":"1184","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","England":"England","Pyvelesdon, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England"},"en":{"1180–":"1180–Deceased","1180–Male":"1180–Deceased","1184–Female":"1184–Deceased","1198–1272":"1198–1272","1155–Male":"1155–Deceased","1160–Female":"1160–Deceased","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1155":"1155","1198":"1198","1272":"1272","1184":"1184","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","England":"England","Pyvelesdon, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Puleston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Puleston (Shrops), which is recorded as  <i>Plivesdone</i> in 1086 and  <i>Pivelesdon’</i> in 1200. The place-name probably derives from an Old English personal name * <i>Peofel</i> (genitive * <i>Peofeles</i>) + Old English  <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’.  See also  Pilson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Pilson","meanings":["English (Lancashire):","perhaps a variant of <b>Puleston</b>, a habitational name from the Shropshire placename Puleston, or, alternatively, a variant of   Poulson   with unrounding of the vowel.","perhaps a variant of <i>Pelson</i> (now rare or extinct in Britain), from the Middle English personal name <i>Pell</i> (see   Pell  ) + <i>son</i>."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":35,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":44,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":79,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Richard de Puleston was born in 1180, in Shropshire, England, his father, Roger de Pyvelesdon, was 25 and his mother, Mrs Roger de Pyvelesdon, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Alice Lewis. He died in England."},"et":{"1180–":"1180–Surnud","1180–Male":"1180–Surnud","1184–Female":"1184–Surnud","1198–1272":"1198–1272","1155–Male":"1155–Surnud","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1155":"1155","1198":"1198","1272":"1272","1184":"1184","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","England":"England","Pyvelesdon, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"1180–":"1180–Kuollut","1180–Male":"1180–Kuollut","1184–Female":"1184–Kuollut","1198–1272":"1198–1272","1155–Male":"1155–Kuollut","1160–Female":"1160–Kuollut","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1155":"1155","1198":"1198","1272":"1272","1184":"1184","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","England":"England","Pyvelesdon, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England"},"fr":{"1180–":"1180–Décédé","1180–Male":"1180–Décédé","1184–Female":"1184–Décédée","1198–1272":"1198–1272","1155–Male":"1155–Décédé","1160–Female":"1160–Décédée","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1155":"1155","1198":"1198","1272":"1272","1184":"1184","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","Pyvelesdon, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Sir Richard de Puleston est né en 1180, à Shropshire, Angleterre, son père, Roger de Pyvelesdon, avait 25 ans et sa mère, Mrs Roger de Pyvelesdon, avait 21 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Alice Lewis. Il est décédé à Angleterre."},"de":{"1180–":"1180–Verstorben","1180–Male":"1180–Verstorben","1184–Female":"1184–Verstorben","1198–1272":"1198–1272","1155–Male":"1155–Verstorben","1160–Female":"1160–Verstorben","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1155":"1155","1198":"1198","1272":"1272","